`crates/` is the workspace root for the CTX system: a family of independent binaries/libraries that together let an agent read, write, verify, sandbox, and re-summarize a repo's `.context/` sidecar tree under enforced access control. No shared library code lives directly here — every subdirectory is its own crate with its own `Cargo.toml`, and cross-crate coupling happens only through published Rust APIs or JSON/wire contracts, never through file-path assumptions.

`ctx-core` is the dependency root: it defines the single canonical access gate (secret/binary/gitignored deny) that `ctx-access` delegates to entirely and that `ctx-scan`/`ctx-summarize` build scope-matching on top of. `ctx-summarize` is the only sanctioned writer of `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files, invoked either directly or via `ctx-scan`'s staleness-driven orchestration; `ctx-access` is the only sanctioned reader/writer of source files for agents, enforcing read-before-write and rollup-before-list ordering. `ctx-context` is a read-only consumer of the same `.ctx`/rollup chain, serving it into Claude Code hooks. `ctx-check` and `ctx-verify` are parallel but independently-evolved verification brokers — both shell out to cargo/clippy/fmt and emit capped JSON reports, but they define separate `Report`/`Diagnostic` model types with no shared crate between them; a fix to one's diagnostic-capping or status-precedence logic does not propagate to the other. `ctx-cage` is the outermost layer, sandboxing an agent process and brokering its tool calls (including `ctx-access`, `ctx-verify`, `ctx-scan`) through an allowlist — its embedded `cage-rules.md` must be kept consistent with whatever tool contracts those other crates actually expose.

Two independent scope-matching implementations exist — `ctx-scan`'s walker/hash logic and `ctx-summarize`'s `fs::scope_matcher` — and must stay behaviorally consistent even though neither depends on the other's matcher code directly. Every crate here isolates real filesystem/process/clock I/O behind an `Env`/`Fs`/`Runner`-style trait, letting each crate's `tests/` (or in `ctx-access`'s case, `FakeEnv`) exercise full logic without touching disk — this pattern is the norm across the workspace, not an accident local to one crate. No `intent.md` exists at this level, so no divergence can be assessed here; check each child crate's own rollup for its own divergence status.